### 1. (Coarsened) Exact Matching

step 1 matching, step 2 estimation.


::: {.cell hash='07_matching_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-4_a072d5e4f64060bb2ddb3a95f235f2ac'}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Matching
cem <- matchit(card ~ avg_purch + age + sex + pre_avg_purch,
               data = data, 
               method = 'cem', 
               estimand = 'ATE')
summary(cem)
```

Also including a Coarse Exact Matching with coarsion on cutpoints age and sex. This maybe wrong, but the graph looks pretty interesting.


::: {.cell hash='07_matching_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-5_76476211fd66ed3235dc9f2235c71f60'}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Custom coarsening
# (1) Matching
cutpoints <- list(age = seq(16, 25, 60), sex = seq(0, 1))
cem_coars <- matchit(card ~ avg_purch + age + sex + pre_avg_purch,
                     data = data, 
                     method = 'cem', 
                     estimand = 'ATE',
                     cutpoints = cutpoints)

# Covariate balance
summary(cem_coars)
```

### 2. Nearest-Neighbor Matching


::: {.cell hash='07_matching_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-6_9dc7448d93a40b293dcb3406960c602a'}

```{.r .cell-code}
# (1) Matching
# replace: one-to-one or one-to-many matching
nn <- matchit(card ~ avg_purch + age + sex + pre_avg_purch,
              data = data,
              method = "nearest",
              distance = "mahalanobis",
              replace = T)

# Covariate Balance
summary(nn)
```

### 3. Inverse Probability Weighting


::: {.cell hash='07_matching_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-7_dc73e1c3d400b25f486d5add59445fca'}

```{.r .cell-code}
# (1) Propensity scores
model_prop <- glm(card ~ avg_purch + age + sex + pre_avg_purch,
                  data = data,
                  family = binomial(link = "logit"))
summary(model_prop)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```{.r .cell-code}
# Add propensities to table
df_aug <- data %>% mutate(propensity = predict(model_prop, type = "response"))
# Extend data by IPW scores
df_ipw <- df_aug %>% mutate(
  ipw = (card/propensity) + ((1-card) / (1-propensity)))

# Look at data with IPW scores
df_ipw %>% 
  select(card, age, sex, avg_purch, pre_avg_purch, propensity, ipw)
```
